=== Guinegate ===
The '''Battle of Guinegate''' or '''Battle of the Spurs''' took place on August 16, 1513. As part of the [[War of the League of Cambrai|Holy League]] under the on-going [[Italian Wars]], English and [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] troops under [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] and [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] surprised and routed a body of French cavalry under [[Jacques de La Palice]].

The English army was provided by Cardinal [[Thomas Wolsey]] and combined several different types of martial forces, and included [[cavalry]], [[artillery]], [[infantry]] and [[longbow]]s using hardened steel arrows designed to penetrate armour more effectively. The French forces were mostly companies of [[gendarme (historical)|gendarmes]] and [[pikemen]], with some other mixed forces as well.

Called the "Battle of the Spurs" because of the haste of the French horse to leave the battlefield, it took place at [[Guinegate]] (now ''Enguinegatte'', [[France]]), hence its name:

{{bquote|A French cavalry force, which had come to succour the besieged town of Therouanne, suddenly found itself opposite the Anglo-Imperial army, the size and position of which it had misjudged.  Repelled by the latter<U+2019>s artillery, the French turned and fled, with English and Burgundian cavalry in hot pursuit.''[http://www.hrp.org.uk/NewsAndMedia/youngHenry.aspx]}}

At the end of the battle the cities of [[Therouanne]] and [[Tournai]] were in the hands of Henry VIII of England.

=== Flodden Field ===
{{details|Battle of Flodden Field}}

The kingdoms of [[Early Modern France|France]] and [[Scotland in the Late Middle Ages|Scotland]] had traditionally enjoyed a [[Auld Alliance|close diplomatic relationship]], reflected in a defensive treaty signed between the two kingdoms in 1512. When [[Henry VIII|Henry]] crossed the [[English Channel]] to campaign in [[Early Modern France|France]], the [[Louis XII of France|King of France]] activated the treaty, sending arms, money and military advisers to [[James IV of Scotland]] to encourage him to fulfil his obligations, in the hope that this would draw English resources away from the invasion of [[Early Modern France|France]]. [[James IV of Scotland|James]] crossed the border with a force of some 35,000 men, including 5,000 French advisers<ref>Guest, Ken, and Denise Guest, ''British Battles'', p. 80</ref>. He was opposed by an English force under [[Thomas Howard, 2nd Duke of Norfolk|the Earl of Surrey]]. The two sides met on 9th September, 1513, near the village of Flodden. The Scottish army was heavily defeated, losing some 9,000 men and many nobles, including [[James IV of Scotland|King James]], the King's [[Alexander Stewart (Archbishop of St Andrews)|illegitimate son]], and twelve [[Earl|earls]].<ref>Guest, Ken, and Denise Guest, ''British Battles'', p. 85</ref>

=== La Motta ===
The '''Battle of La Motta''', also known as the '''Battle of Schio''', '''Battle of Vicenza''' or '''Battle of Creazzo''', which took place on October 7, 1513 between the [[Republic of Venice]] and [[Spain]], was a significant battle of the [[War of the League of Cambrai]].  A Venetian army under [[Bartolomeo d'Alviano]] attempted to prevent the Spanish under [[Ramon de Cardona]] from withdrawing from the [[Veneto]], but was defeated and scattered.

