== Italian War of 1521<U+2013>26 ==
{{details|Italian War of 1521<U+2013>1526}}

=== Pampeluna ===
The '''Battle of Pampeluna''' (also spelled [[Pamplona]]) occurred on May 20, 1521, between [[France|French]]-backed [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarrese]] and [[Spain|Spanish]] troops, during the [[Spanish conquest of Iberian Navarre|Spanish conquest of Iberian Navarre]] and in the context of the [[Italian War of 1521<U+2013>1526]]. Most Navarrese towns rised at once against the Spanish, who had [[Kingdom of Navarre#Castilian conquest|invaded Navarre]] in 1512. The Spanish resisted the siege sheltered inside the city castle, but they eventually surrendered and the Navarrese took control of the town and the castle of Pamplona.

It was at this battle that Inigo Lopez de Loyola, better known as [[St. Ignatius of Loyola]], suffered severe injuries, a French cannonball shattering his leg. His meditations during his long recovery set him on the road of a conversion of life from soldier to priest. He would eventually found the [[Society of Jesus]] (the Jesuits), and create the [[Spiritual Exercises of Ignatius of Loyola|Spiritual Exercises]], which is the basis for the idea of "retreats" as an experience of prayer as practiced in the [[Roman Catholic Church]].

=== Noain-Esquiroz ===
The '''Battle of Noain-Esquiroz''' was fought near [[Pamplona]] on June 30, 1521, during the [[Italian War of 1521]].  A makeshift [[Spain|Spanish]] army consisting mostly of [[Crown of Castile|Castilian]] troops defeated the Navarrese and [[France|French]] forces under [[Henry d'Albret]] and Lesparre, driving them out of Iberian [[Navarre]].

=== M<U+00E9>zi<U+00E8>res ===
The '''Siege of M<U+00E9>zi<U+00E8>res''' (1521) took place during the [[Italian War of 1521]].  An [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] army besieged the city (now part of [[Charleville-M<U+00E9>zi<U+00E8>res]]), which was defended by [[France|French]] troops under the command of the [[Chevalier de Bayard]] and [[Anne de Montmorency]]; the siege was unsuccessful, and the determined French resistance gave [[Francis I of France|Francis I]] time to concentrate his forces against [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]].

=== Tournai ===
The '''Siege of Tournai''' (1521) took place during the [[Italian War of 1521]].  An [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] army besieged the city of [[Tournai]], capturing it from the [[France|French]] in late November; it would remain a [[Habsburg]] possession until the independence of [[Belgium]].

=== Bicocca ===
{{details|Battle of Bicocca}}

=== Genoa ===
The '''Siege of Genoa''' (May 20, 1522<U+2013>May 30, 1522) was conducted by an army of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] under the command of Spanish General [[Fernando d'Avalos]] and Italian condottiero [[Prospero Colonna (condottiero)|Prospero Colonna]] against the [[France|French]] forces defending the Italian city.  Since [[Genoa]] had refused to surrender, the Imperial troops were permitted to loot the city once it had fallen.

=== Sesia ===
The '''Battle of the Sesia''' (April 30, 1524) was a battle in the [[Italian War of 1521]] fought near the [[Sesia River]] that saw the [[Habsburg]] forces under [[Charles de Lannoy]] inflict a decisive defeat on the [[France|French]] under [[Admiral Bonnivet]] and the [[Fran<U+00E7>ois I, Duc d'Estouteville|comte de St. Pol]], forcing the latter to withdraw from Lombardy.

=== Marseille ===
The '''Siege of Marseille''' (August<U+2013>September 1524) was conducted by an [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] army under [[Charles III, Duke of Bourbon|Charles de Bourbon]] (who had recently betrayed [[Francis I of France|Francis I]]) and [[Fernando de Avalos]] against the [[France|French]] defenders of [[Marseille]].  Although Avalos heavily looted the surrounding countryside, he was unsuccessful in seizing the city; and, faced with the arrival of French reinforcements, called off the siege in September.

