== Italian War of 1542<U+2013>46 ==
{{details|Italian War of 1542<U+2013>1546}}

=== Nice ===
{{details|Siege of Nice}}
The Siege of Nice took place in August 1543, during the [[Italian War of 1542]], when a combined [[Franco-Ottoman alliance|Franco-Ottoman force]] attacked and captured the [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] city of [[Nice]].<ref>Arnold, ''Renaissance at War,'' 180; Blockmans, ''Emperor Charles V,'' 72<U+2013>73; Oman, ''Art of War,'' 213.</ref>

=== D<U+00FC>ren ===

=== Ceresole ===
{{details|Battle of Ceresole}}

=== Serravalle ===
The '''Battle of Serravalle''' took place on June 2, 1544, during the [[Italian War of 1542]].  A [[Spain|Spanish]]-[[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] army under [[Alfonso d'Avalos d'Aquino, Marquis del Vasto]], defeated a force of freshly-raised [[Italy|Italian]] mercenaries in [[France|French]] service, commanded by [[Pietro Strozzi]] and [[Giovan Francesco Orsini]], Count of [[Pitigliano]].

=== St. Dizier ===
The '''Siege of St. Dizier''' took place in the summer of [[1544]], during the [[Italian War of 1542]], when the [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] army of [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] attacked the [[France|French]] city of [[St. Dizier]] at the beginning of its advance into [[Champagne, France|Champagne]].  The siege was already underway when Charles V himself arrived with an army of 14,100 (including 1600 [[sapper|sappers]]) on 13 July. The next day an imperial commander, [[Ren<U+00E9> of Ch<U+00E2>lon]], [[The Prince of Orange|Prince of Orange]], was struck by a shot from the defenders, and died the next day with the Emperor by his bed (his title and lands going to his famous cousin, [[William the Silent]]). On 23 July French outposts near the besieged town were overrun, but a French army under the command of the [[Dauphin of France|Dauphin]] [[Henry II of France|Henry]] maintained an observing position at Jalons. On August 17 the town surrendered. Charles elected not to attack the Dauphin's army and instead pressed on to [[Soissons]].

